<paragraph blockId="5.[192,1441,1176,1628]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">
In this species, the 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[490,505,1176,1190]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">th</superScript>
abdominal segment has only one pair of exsertile vesicles, placing it in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Paclt" authorityName="Paclt" box="[316,525,1211,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Verhoeffilis">
<emphasis box="[316,454,1211,1235]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Verhoeffilis</emphasis>
Paclt
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authority="Silvestri" authorityName="Silvestri" box="[596,879,1211,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submutans">
<emphasis box="[596,764,1211,1235]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">P. submutans</emphasis>
Silvestri
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Silvestri" authorityName="Silvestri" box="[892,1212,1211,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persquamosus">
<emphasis box="[892,1098,1212,1235]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">P. persquamosus</emphasis>
Silvestri
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Silvestri" authorityName="Silvestri" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calcaratus">
<emphasis box="[1280,1440,1211,1235]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">P. calcaratus</emphasis>
Silvestri
</taxonomicName>
, and distinguishing it from 
<taxonomicName authority="Silvestri" authorityName="Silvestri" box="[662,961,1244,1268]" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis box="[662,843,1244,1268]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">P. californicus</emphasis>
Silvestri
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Silvestri" authorityName="Silvestri" box="[978,1234,1244,1268]" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="superior">
<emphasis box="[978,1116,1244,1267]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">P. superior</emphasis>
Silvestri
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Wygodzinsky and Schmidt" authorityName="Wygodzinsky and Schmidt" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saltator">
<emphasis box="[1308,1440,1244,1268]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">P. saltator</emphasis>
Wygodzinsky and Schmidt
</taxonomicName>
in the nominal subgenus, which have two pairs of exsertile vesicles. The apical segments of the maxillary and labial palpi in this species lack strong spines, and it is known only from 
<collectingRegion box="[256,376,1342,1366]" country="United States of America" name="Arkansas" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Arkansas</collectingRegion>
, separating it from the other species in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Paclt" authorityName="Paclt" box="[1025,1163,1342,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Machilidae" genus="Pedetontus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Verhoeffilis">
<emphasis box="[1025,1163,1342,1366]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Verhoeffilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which are also mostly found in the Pacific Coast states and Canadian provinces (
<bibRefCitation author="Allen" box="[905,1042,1375,1399]" firstAuthor="Allen" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" pagination="195 - 198" refId="ref6280" refString="Allen, R. T. 1995. Pedetontus gershneri, a new species of Machilidae from the interior highlands of North America (Insecta: Microcoryphia). Entomological News 106: 195 - 198." type="journal article" year="1995">Allen 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[192,1441,1176,1628]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">
This species was previously known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[874,928,1408,1432]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">type</typeStatus>
series collected on Magazine Mountain, 
<collectingRegion box="[192,309,1440,1464]" country="United States of America" name="Arkansas" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Arkansas</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Allen" box="[323,458,1440,1464]" firstAuthor="Allen" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" pagination="195 - 198" refId="ref6280" refString="Allen, R. T. 1995. Pedetontus gershneri, a new species of Machilidae from the interior highlands of North America (Insecta: Microcoryphia). Entomological News 106: 195 - 198." type="journal article" year="1995">Allen 1995</bibRefCitation>
), and the specimens from the MEM were also collected at the 
<typeStatus box="[1205,1258,1441,1465]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">type</typeStatus>
locality. While this species was described from moist forest floor among leaf and pine litter, 
<bibRefCitation author="Allen" box="[1125,1273,1473,1497]" firstAuthor="Allen" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" pagination="195 - 198" refId="ref6280" refString="Allen, R. T. 1995. Pedetontus gershneri, a new species of Machilidae from the interior highlands of North America (Insecta: Microcoryphia). Entomological News 106: 195 - 198." type="journal article" year="1995">Allen (1995)</bibRefCitation>
also reported 
<taxonomicName authority="Silvestri" authorityName="Silvestri" authorityYear="1911" box="[192,525,1505,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Meinertellidae" genus="Machiloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banksi">
<emphasis box="[192,420,1505,1529]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Machiloides banksi</emphasis>
Silvestri
</taxonomicName>
from xeric rock ledge habitat elsewhere on Magazine Mountain. It is therefore interesting that these species with apparently differing habitat preferences were both collected in the same sample on 
<date box="[398,562,1571,1595]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" value="1989-05-17">17 May 1989</date>
. Perhaps pitfall traps were placed in intermediate habitats or multiple pitfall traps from different habitats were composited.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
